00:03:33.490 --> 00:03:34.850
The really cool thing
about these books;

00:03:34.850 --> 00:03:37.500
not only were they really
popular in the ‘80s and ‘90s,

00:03:37.500 --> 00:03:42.280
but today there's 184 stories, and
they have formats such as Braille,

00:03:42.280 --> 00:03:45.390
and voice-activated interactive-audio
books, so they're really inclusive.

00:03:46.870 --> 00:03:49.310
Fast forward a few years
and, of course, I'm thrilled

00:03:49.310 --> 00:03:51.750
to see my own children
reading these books.

00:03:51.750 --> 00:03:54.540
But I never really stopped to
consider why these books were

00:03:54.540 --> 00:03:57.180
so engaging until
I became a parent.

00:03:57.180 --> 00:03:59.890
And now I see how this type
of book became so popular

00:03:59.890 --> 00:04:03.250
because it's really about choice,
and the freedom of choice.

00:04:03.250 --> 00:04:05.610
So if you think back again
to when you were young,

00:04:05.610 --> 00:04:08.100
you probably didn't have
much control over your life.

00:04:08.100 --> 00:04:10.390
But when you read a
type of book like this,

00:04:10.390 --> 00:04:12.060
suddenly you control everything.

00:04:12.060 --> 00:04:15.260
You make all the choices,
you're empowered, you're the master

00:04:15.260 --> 00:04:16.260
of your own destiny.

00:04:18.660 --> 00:04:22.280
So we make a series of choices
every day: get up early, work out,

00:04:22.280 --> 00:04:24.190
and hit the snooze button.

00:04:24.190 --> 00:04:27.150
I did sleep in today,
but I still worked out, so good job.

00:04:27.150 --> 00:04:33.070
Made a double-foam latte or
green cafe tea, tabs or spaces.

00:04:33.070 --> 00:04:35.180
I'm a tabs kind of person.

00:04:35.180 --> 00:04:37.910
These choices,
even the very insignificant ones,

00:04:37.910 --> 00:04:41.310
shape our identities, and forms
our perspectives on the world.

00:04:41.310 --> 00:04:44.450
And in today's modern landscape,
we've come to expect a broad range

00:04:44.450 --> 00:04:47.620
of choices regardless of the products
or services that we're looking at.

00:04:47.620 --> 00:04:50.670
However,
this has not always been the case.

00:04:50.670 --> 00:04:52.560
You saw that maybe
come up on the screen,

00:04:52.560 --> 00:04:55.110
but we have the very
first font family.

00:04:55.110 --> 00:04:59.010
There used to be only one: Johannes
Gutenberg and the Printing Press

00:04:59.010 --> 00:05:00.540
in 1440.

00:05:01.700 --> 00:05:07.790
The first set of a web colors, MIT,
the X10R3, which later became X11.

00:05:07.790 --> 00:05:10.780
There were only 69 basic shades.

00:05:10.780 --> 00:05:14.210
Technically, if you are counting
things like dark-red, you have 138,

00:05:14.210 --> 00:05:15.590
but just a limited palette.

00:05:16.840 --> 00:05:19.420
Then in 1995,
a United State programmer named

00:05:19.421 --> 00:05:20.710
Brandan Eich developed

00:05:20.710 --> 00:05:24.910
a new scripting language called
Mocha, later renamed to LiveScript,

00:05:24.910 --> 00:05:27.360
and then also onto JavaScript.

00:05:29.240 --> 00:05:33.080
Fast forward to today,
and we have over 650,000 web fonts

00:05:33.081 --> 00:05:34.360
to choose from.

00:05:35.520 --> 00:05:42.760
The number of colors in the
HEX system now are 16,177,216,

00:05:42.760 --> 00:05:43.520
to be precise.

00:05:44.960 --> 00:05:48.380
And I said roughly over
100, let's say,

00:05:48.380 --> 00:05:53.330
public JavaScript facing web
frameworks and libraries, right?

00:05:53.330 --> 00:05:56.550
There's probably many,
many more that are proprietary.

00:05:59.080 --> 00:06:02.620
So thinking about those
concepts of choice.

00:06:02.620 --> 00:06:04.380
So this is all great.

00:06:04.380 --> 00:06:06.130
Life is the sum of
all your choices.

00:06:06.130 --> 00:06:08.460
This quote is on the
screen, by Albert Camus.

00:06:08.460 --> 00:06:11.020
He’s a famous French philosopher.

00:06:11.020 --> 00:06:13.710
So what happens when
you don't have a choice?

00:06:13.710 --> 00:06:15.840
What if that choice is taken away?

00:06:15.840 --> 00:06:18.000
How do you respond when
you don't have any choice?

00:06:18.000 --> 00:06:21.250
And not surprisingly,
many studies at all kinds

00:06:21.250 --> 00:06:23.540
of different academic areas
have shown that feelings

00:06:23.540 --> 00:06:27.330
of powerlessness can lead to
negative outcomes like depression,

00:06:27.330 --> 00:06:30.020
anxiety,
a feeling of worthlessness.

00:06:30.020 --> 00:06:33.810
So a lot of negative feelings
when choice has been removed

00:06:33.810 --> 00:06:34.810
from the equation.

00:06:35.880 --> 00:06:38.690
So with the abundance of options
we're used to these days,

00:06:38.690 --> 00:06:41.160
and all the positive
aspects of choice

00:06:41.160 --> 00:06:44.170
as independent researchers
have found, why is it that

00:06:44.170 --> 00:06:48.560
in the digital space, we really often
don't give our users many choices?

00:06:48.560 --> 00:06:50.260
By allowing our users
to make choices,

00:06:50.260 --> 00:06:53.800
we could help them accomplish tasks,
connect more easily with others,

00:06:53.800 --> 00:06:55.030
and ultimately empower them.

00:06:58.160 --> 00:07:00.950
What does it mean when we
talk about accessible choice?

00:07:00.950 --> 00:07:04.160
That's all good and fine and
generalized in the world,

00:07:04.160 --> 00:07:06.250
but what are we talking about
specifically when it comes

00:07:06.250 --> 00:07:10.160
to digital accessibility,
and CSS specifically?

00:07:10.160 --> 00:07:13.990
The concept of choice gets
more complicated, of course,

00:07:13.990 --> 00:07:16.560
when you bring disabilities
into the discussion.

00:07:16.560 --> 00:07:19.450
You have to make considerations
for each disability type,

00:07:19.450 --> 00:07:21.350
speaking in a very broad sense.

00:07:21.350 --> 00:07:25.250
But also on the individual level,
based on the day, environment,

00:07:25.250 --> 00:07:30.310
assistive tech, device support,
operating system, browsers, versions,

00:07:30.310 --> 00:07:31.890
settings, et cetera, et cetera.

00:07:31.890 --> 00:07:34.240
It can get a little
bit overwhelming.

00:07:34.240 --> 00:07:36.260
But it's up to us
developers and designers

00:07:36.260 --> 00:07:39.510
to consider these complex needs
and offer accessible choices.

00:07:40.790 --> 00:07:43.060
Just kind of a side
note, because we all have

00:07:43.060 --> 00:07:44.440
