These are separate entities.

00:41:00.580 --> 00:41:02.400
But you could apply your own.

00:41:02.400 --> 00:41:05.100
Maybe create a new,
like, guideline.

00:41:05.100 --> 00:41:06.100
That'd be pretty cool.

00:41:08.150 --> 00:41:12.280
 <v Ben> Andrew asked: Is providing
a theme toggle on your website

00:41:12.280 --> 00:41:14.920
for light or dark
necessary or overkill

00:41:14.920 --> 00:41:17.188
if you're already using
prefers-color-scheme

00:41:17.189 --> 00:41:19.760
to automatically set colors
across your WordPress theme?

00:41:19.760 --> 00:41:23.450
Or is it a good idea because it
helps further support user choice?

00:41:23.450 --> 00:41:24.790
 <v Carie> That's a
really good question.

00:41:24.790 --> 00:41:26.170
Yes, [Inaudible 00:41:25].

00:41:27.700 --> 00:41:31.750
So when light/dark mode wasn't a
thing, you could use a little bit

00:41:31.750 --> 00:41:32.860
of JavaScript code.

00:41:32.860 --> 00:41:36.590
Usually, it’s like turning on and
turning off classes to essentially do

00:41:36.590 --> 00:41:39.530
what we can do in the operating
system settings right now.

00:41:39.530 --> 00:41:41.990
So I think for more like
the experimental ones,

00:41:41.990 --> 00:41:47.040
like prefers-reduced-data,
the ones around the contrast,

00:41:47.040 --> 00:41:50.320
but different options, that would
be pretty cool because those things,

00:41:50.320 --> 00:41:53.420
as we saw in the settings,
aren't always available.

00:41:53.420 --> 00:41:55.790
When you get to ones like
prefers-reduced-motion

00:41:55.790 --> 00:42:00.430
and like light/dark modes,
I feel like we've gotten to a point

00:42:00.430 --> 00:42:02.930
of saturation where
people know where that is.

00:42:02.930 --> 00:42:04.150
I don't want to make assumptions.

00:42:05.650 --> 00:42:08.430
So you could maybe have
both if you wanted to.

00:42:08.430 --> 00:42:11.270
But I'm thinking more of like the
experimental ones are the ones

00:42:11.270 --> 00:42:14.430
that operating systems and
browsers are not fully supporting.

00:42:14.430 --> 00:42:16.110
That'd be kind of cool.

00:42:16.110 --> 00:42:18.084
Because, just like light/dark mode,

00:42:18.085 --> 00:42:20.340
that's how we started
the conversation

00:42:20.340 --> 00:42:21.260
around that one.

00:42:21.260 --> 00:42:22.820
The same thing with reduced motion.

00:42:22.820 --> 00:42:25.730
Like, that's how I first was
introduced to those concepts.

00:42:25.730 --> 00:42:26.580
It's like, Oh, that's cool.

00:42:26.580 --> 00:42:29.410
I'll just toggle it. And now
there's other CSS media feature

00:42:29.410 --> 00:42:30.690
that does this.

00:42:30.690 --> 00:42:33.330
So that's a really tricky question,
though, because that assumes

00:42:33.330 --> 00:42:35.790
that the user knows how
to toggle those on and off

00:42:35.790 --> 00:42:37.140
on their operating system.

00:42:37.140 --> 00:42:43.610
 <v Ben> The way we've done that is
to default to the user's OS level

00:42:43.610 --> 00:42:46.950
or browser-level setting, but also
give them an override control.

00:42:46.950 --> 00:42:48.200
 <v Carie> Yes, that's cool, Yes.

00:42:48.200 --> 00:42:50.540
Like a little cookie,
like a setting cookie.

00:42:50.540 --> 00:42:51.030
 <v Ben> Yes.

00:42:51.030 --> 00:42:54.820
So if that user doesn't happen
to know what an OS setting is,

00:42:54.820 --> 00:42:59.290
they can just switch it on depending
on their need for that day.

00:42:59.290 --> 00:43:01.520
Although, in some cases,
that may be overkill.

00:43:02.060 --> 00:43:02.940
 <v Carie> Talk to Ben.

00:43:02.940 --> 00:43:05.410
It sounds like Ben's
got it figured out.

00:43:05.410 --> 00:43:05.640
[chuckles]

00:43:05.640 --> 00:43:07.870
I do like that combination, yes.

00:43:10.070 --> 00:43:15.060
 <v Ben> Deneb said: Great
job showing browser support.

00:43:15.060 --> 00:43:18.340
I'm curious how many people actually
know how to edit their settings

00:43:19.650 --> 00:43:20.860
to choose those adventures.

00:43:20.860 --> 00:43:21.520
[Inaudible 00:43:20]

00:43:21.520 --> 00:43:22.670
is how often those are used.

00:43:22.670 --> 00:43:24.210
So I guess that's
kind of related to...

00:43:24.210 --> 00:43:26.580
 <v Carie> Let's
just do shrug emoji.

00:43:26.580 --> 00:43:27.802
[laughter]

00:43:27.802 --> 00:43:30.840
I don't know if that's an option
here in the webinar, but yes.

00:43:30.840 --> 00:43:33.710
Some of these, you know,
more of the cutting-edge...

00:43:33.710 --> 00:43:36.040
And by cutting-edge, I mean,
they've been around for a bit,

00:43:36.040 --> 00:43:39.200
but the ones that are starting
to be adapted by the OSs

00:43:39.200 --> 00:43:43.370
or adopted by OSs and the
browsers, it's kind of a little bit

00:43:43.370 --> 00:43:46.090
of a fun Wild West, where we
really don't know how it's going

00:43:46.090 --> 00:43:46.770
to shake out.

00:43:46.770 --> 00:43:48.880
And this is the current state.

00:43:48.880 --> 00:43:50.690
Like I said, in the
spring, there was, like,

00:43:50.690 --> 00:43:52.710
no support for like
the forced-colors.

00:43:52.710 --> 00:43:56.560
And now there's like 80-something,
you know, next time I do this talk.

00:43:56.560 --> 00:44:00.280
You know, down the road a couple
months, you know, surprise,

00:44:00.280 --> 00:44:04.280
maybe it’ll be 100%
somewhere or close.

00:44:04.280 --> 00:44:04.710
[chuckles]

00:44:04.710 --> 00:44:05.670
 <v Ben> Yes.

00:44:05.670 --> 00:44:08.530
Actually, that that reminds
me of a question I had.

00:44:08.530 --> 00:44:10.970
You talked about how every
time you give the talk,

00:44:10.970 --> 00:44:12.160
the features have changed.

00:44:12.160 --> 00:44:12.540
 <v Carie> Yes.

00:44:12.540 --> 00:44:16.790
 <v Ben> How do you keep up with
the evolution of those features

00:44:16.790 --> 00:44:17.890
and new releases?

00:44:17.890 --> 00:44:23.600
And how do you build that into
your process to keep up with that

00:44:23.600 --> 00:44:25.170
on a longer project?

00:44:25.170 --> 00:44:25.500
 <v Carie> Yes.

00:44:25.500 --> 00:44:28.710
And this is only the third
time I've ever given this talk.

00:44:28.710 --> 00:44:31.280
I don't do too many repeat talks.

00:44:31.280 --> 00:44:32.270
This is probably the max.

00:44:32.270 --> 00:44:34.990
Maybe I'll do one more,
but I love the concept.

00:44:34.990 --> 00:44:38.870
But this idea of the can I
use is going to have a lot

00:44:38.870 --> 00:44:39.790
of up-to-date information.

00:44:39.790 --> 00:44:43.780
Although, if you're like a big nerd
and want to be on top of things,

00:44:43.780 --> 00:44:46.180
there are all kinds of communities
that you can join specific

00:44:46.180 --> 00:44:51.380
to those browsers, or dig into those
bug reports, accessibility bugs.

00:44:51.380 --> 00:44:54.690
You know, obviously, some of them in
the browser space that are like 10,

00:44:54.690 --> 00:44:56.370
14 years old, right?

00:44:56.370 --> 00:45:00.240
So don't be surprised to
see some of the, you know,

00:45:00.240 --> 00:45:01.570
pushback against some of those.

00:45:01.570 --> 00:45:03.410
But it's interesting to see.

00:45:03.410 --> 00:45:08.450
There’s some people who are starting
to, at least, on the Chrome side

00:45:08.450 --> 00:45:13.340
and the Mozilla side and the
Safari side, push these things.

00:45:13.340 --> 00:45:15.940
And they're starting to see
the value and how it could be

00:45:15.940 --> 00:45:18.300
for digital
accessibility especially.

00:45:18.300 --> 00:45:23.260
It’s like giving them a
little bit more of a push

00:45:23.260 --> 00:45:26.120
to get these things
integrated into the browser

00:45:26.120 --> 00:45:27.873
and operating systems now.

00:45:27.873 --> 00:45:28.480
 <v Ben> Yes.

00:45:30.200 --> 00:45:33.360
At one point, you also mentioned
that some of them can be in conflict.

00:45:33.360 --> 00:45:40.060
So as a dev, do you have to
then do anything in your code

00:45:40.060 --> 00:45:42.960
to prioritize which
preferences get respected?

00:45:44.900 --> 00:45:46.130
What's your responsibility there?

00:45:47.153 --> 00:45:50.380
 <v Carie> I mean, really, your
responsibility is what you want it

00:45:50.380 --> 00:45:53.200
to be, because like I said,
you don't have any obligation to do

00:45:53.200 --> 00:45:54.060
any of these things.

00:45:54.060 --> 00:45:57.090
So it's this idea of that,
What do you want to do?

00:45:57.090 --> 00:46:00.030
And part of that is talking to
your users and kind of asking them,

00:46:00.030 --> 00:46:02.430
you know, Hey,
what is it that you prefer?

00:46:02.430 --> 00:46:03.550
And then working around that.

00:46:03.550 --> 00:46:06.460
There are going to be certain ones
like the prefers-reduce-motion

00:46:06.460 --> 00:46:09.100
and the light/dark mode
that I think are essential.

00:46:09.100 --> 00:46:13.140
There'll be other ones like the
contrast one, more contrast,

00:46:13.140 --> 00:46:14.140
at least, right?

00:46:14.140 --> 00:46:17.990
So those are the three that I was
thinking of as the bare minimum

00:46:17.990 --> 00:46:20.430
for getting your users
those 16 options.

00:46:20.430 --> 00:46:24.730
I don't think there's any
obligation to anything.

00:46:24.730 --> 00:46:27.540
I don't want to say that,
but just think of it as fun, right?

00:46:27.540 --> 00:46:29.800
This is one of those areas
where I think we can play,

00:46:29.800 --> 00:46:32.440
especially when there aren't
any hard and fast rules.

00:46:32.440 --> 00:46:36.460
So as long as you're adhering,
again, to your WCAG Success Criteria,

00:46:36.460 --> 00:46:41.210
and your levels, and all that
good stuff, this could be a place

00:46:41.210 --> 00:46:43.870
to explore those
options and think about,

00:46:43.870 --> 00:46:47.100
How can we make it that
user experience even greater

00:46:47.100 --> 00:46:53.410
and more enjoyable and delight? Like
a real, true adventure, not a slog.

00:46:53.410 --> 00:46:53.870
[chuckles]

00:46:53.870 --> 00:46:55.560
Isn't that the dream?

00:46:55.560 --> 00:47:00.160
You go to a website or a digital app
and you're just like, This is cool.

00:47:00.160 --> 00:47:00.800
This is awesome.

00:47:00.800 --> 00:47:04.490
I want to show all my friends.
 <v Ben> Yes.

00:47:04.490 --> 00:47:09.010
But it sounds like there's
nothing in the user agent or

00:47:09.010 --> 00:47:12.070
in the browser that necessarily
kind of handles conflict resolution

00:47:12.070 --> 00:47:12.550
that is...

00:47:12.550 --> 00:47:14.460
 <v Carie> Oh, yes.

00:47:14.460 --> 00:47:18.820
There’s certain ones that I've
read that may secede others,

00:47:18.820 --> 00:47:21.370
but then some of them are
on the element level too.

00:47:21.370 --> 00:47:25.250
I'm not remembering off the
top of my head which ones.

00:47:25.250 --> 00:47:30.190
There’s a whole matrix of, like, This
one supersedes this one. But like

00:47:30.190 --> 00:47:32.030
I said, also,
you could chain them together,

00:47:32.030 --> 00:47:35.335
and you could have multiple,
different media features

00:47:35.336 --> 00:47:36.620
on one theme, right?

00:47:36.620 --> 00:47:39.860
So in this particular scenario,
I'm serving this, right?

00:47:39.860 --> 00:47:41.200
And in this one, I'm serving this.

00:47:41.200 --> 00:47:43.650
Like that exponential
kind of concept,

00:47:43.650 --> 00:47:46.720
which hopefully doesn't overwhelm
anyone; that excites people.

00:47:46.720 --> 00:47:51.680
But yes, there's a few
around the forced-colors

00:47:51.680 --> 00:47:53.090
that I remember reading about.

00:47:53.090 --> 00:47:55.340
But experiment is what I would do.

00:47:57.060 --> 00:48:00.040
 <v Ben> I guess then that leads
to, you know,

00:48:00.040 --> 00:48:02.930
my QA team would be asking,
OK, how do we approach

00:48:02.930 --> 00:48:06.190
testing the infinite combinations?
Like,

00:48:06.190 --> 00:48:09.780
where do you draw the line
from your perspective?

00:48:09.780 --> 00:48:12.750
 <v Carie> Yes, I mean, there's
always a line to draw for sure.

00:48:12.750 --> 00:48:15.640
And, you know, this is dreaming
a little bit and talking

00:48:15.640 --> 00:48:19.490
about it like this world
where I'm choosing exactly

00:48:19.490 --> 00:48:22.810
what I want every single time
on every digital products.

00:48:22.810 --> 00:48:24.860
Like, let's go [Inaudible 00:48:24]

00:48:24.860 --> 00:48:27.520
websites, and even made a mobile...
Like, everything.

00:48:27.520 --> 00:48:30.500
I want it to look exactly
what I wanted to look like.

00:48:30.500 --> 00:48:32.520
And maybe we'll get
to that point someday.

00:48:32.520 --> 00:48:36.070
But up until then, you're
going to have some variations.

00:48:36.070 --> 00:48:39.230
Some people will probably push
the envelope a little bit.

00:48:39.230 --> 00:48:43.360
Other one's will be dragging
along begrudgingly behind us

00:48:43.360 --> 00:48:47.980
and saying, like, Hey, guys,
let's get this going. So somewhere

00:48:47.980 --> 00:48:53.600
in the middle of those two scenarios
is probably where you want to be.

00:48:53.600 --> 00:48:55.330
And that sweet spot
will keep changing

00:48:55.330 --> 00:48:59.580
as more browsers are supporting this
and more users are asking for this.

00:48:59.580 --> 00:49:01.560
Because I think that's
another piece of it.

00:49:01.560 --> 00:49:02.609
And because, again,

00:49:02.610 --> 00:49:05.700
we don't want them using
those accessibility overlays.

00:49:05.700 --> 00:49:08.320
We want them to be
making their own choices,

00:49:08.320 --> 00:49:12.350
and having the system that they
want, and the visual interaction

00:49:12.350 --> 00:49:16.890
that they want, but not have to
be dependent on you deciding,

00:49:16.890 --> 00:49:19.990
like, you're going to provide
this through this one program.

00:49:19.990 --> 00:49:23.640
And only you're providing that,
so then when I go to my other site,

00:49:23.640 --> 00:49:26.570
now I'm messed up,
and all my settings are wrong.

00:49:26.570 --> 00:49:29.240
Again, this is part of that too.

00:49:30.430 --> 00:49:33.470
It’s circumventing some of those
issues that come up with that kind

00:49:33.470 --> 00:49:34.210
of product as well.

00:49:35.279 --> 00:49:36.679
 <v Ben> Yes.

